    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "i mean, u said it achieved its \"narrow military objective\" but then said it failed to get stability. but if the end result was just a vacuum that led to a failed state and a huge refugee crisis, doesn't that basically make the whole intervention a failure in the long run? why call it a success at all if it just made things worse?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The initial military success was purely tactical, achieving the immediate goal of regime change and protecting civilians from mass slaughter. However, the long-term failure to establish a functioning, stable government proves that the intervention was a strategic disaster. The resulting state vacuum allowed extremist groups to flourish, directly undermining regional stability in North Africa and the Mediterranean. Therefore, when viewed through the lens of enduring geopolitical order, the intervention must be judged a comprehensive failure.",
      "source": "target",
